  "prompt": "What is the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to law of inertia?",
  "response": "The force applied by a body on an object due to the law of inertia is **zero**.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Law of Inertia:** The law of inertia (Newton's First Law of Motion) states that an object at rest stays at rest, and an object in motion stays in motion with the same speed and in the same direction unless acted upon by a force. It's about resistance to changes in motion.\n*   **Inertia is not a force:** Inertia is a property of matter, not a force. It's the tendency of an object to resist changes in its state of motion.\n*   **No Force Applied:** A body does not actively *apply* a force to maintain its state of motion. It simply *resists* external forces that try to change that state. If there's no external force acting on the body, there's no force being applied \"due to inertia.\"\n\n**Example:**\n\nImagine a hockey puck sitting still on a frictionless ice surface. It stays still due to inertia. There's no force being applied by the puck to itself to remain at rest. If you *do* apply a force (like hitting it with a stick), the puck resists that change in motion *because* of its inertia.\n\nIn essence, the law of inertia tells us what happens when there *isn't* a net force.\n\n**Therefore, the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to the law of inertia is zero.**",
